				\begin{document}$$\overrightarrow {\mathbf{\mu}}$$\end{document}, is the dipole moment operator. In actual calculations, the delta function is replaced with a Gaussian function whose width is taken to be the same for all vibronic contributions54,60. In the case of vibronic models including a few effective modes, the calculated vibronic peaks are separated by an energy related to that of the lower-energy vibrational mode. In these instances, it is a standard practice to use a Gaussian smearing of the vibronic peaks. In order to obtain a smooth profile of the simulated absorption spectra, we used a Gaussian broadening with a width (100 cm−1) set according to the energy of the low-frequency vibration (100 cm−1). We note that this procedure has a negligible impact on the overall width and asymmetry of the simulated absorption spectra. The transition dipole moment, μCT, of the CT absorption can be then obtained via the integration of A(E)/E54.

